name: Ruins at Westerplatte
description: The site of the first battle of World War II.

name: Wisłoujście Fortress
description: This 700-year-old structure is one of the most unique architectural and historic monuments in Gdańsk.

name: Upside-Down House
description: Communism's topsy-turvy effect on Poland has been brought to life in this wacky tourist trap.

name: Gdansk Astronomical Clock
description: A huge wooden clock that is so beautiful its creator was forcibly blinded.

name: Łapalice Castle
description: This imposing 20th-century castle was abandoned before it was ever completed.

name: Hotel Zdrowie
description: A haunting deserted hotel is a favorite with artists and photographers.

name: Malbork Castle
description: This 13th century Gothic brick castle is the largest in the world by surface area.

name: Krzywy Domek - Crooked House
description: This fairytale inspired, warped building houses restaurants, shops, and a radio station.

name: Torpedownia
description: A World War II torpedo launch station abandoned off the Polish coast.

name: Gdańsk Shipyard
description: A floundering Polish shipyard was once the soul of the Solidarity movement that capsized communism.

itemLabel: Old Prussian Hags of Northern Pomerania
name: Old Prussian Hags of Northern Pomerania
description: These rare statues are one of the few remaining material witnesses to Old Prussian culture.

itemLabel: The Three Boar Heads of Gdańsk
name: The Three Boar Heads of Gdańsk
description: A mysterious emblem tucked in an small alleyway is actually the coat of arms of a heroic medieval family.

name: Cemetery of Lost Cemeteries
description: Memorial to the lost dead of Gdansk, whose resting places were destroyed during World War II.

name: Dwór Artusa
description: A merchant court dedicated to the fictitious King Arthur is heavily adorned with bizarre Renaissance art.

name: Fahrenheit Monument
description: This antique thermometer honors the creator of the first universal temperature scale.

name: Falowiec
description: This Communist-era residential block is one of the longest residential building in Europe.

itemLabel: Monument to the Defenders of the Polish Post Office
name: Monument to the Defenders of the Polish Post Office
description: Modern art commemorates one of the first military actions of World War II.

name: Carthusian Church Monastery
description: The coffin-shaped church was once home to monks who slept in coffins.

name: Tower Clock Museum
description: This museum in the tower of the oldest church in Gdańsk, is home to centuries-old time-keeping devices and the world's first pulsar clock.

name: St. Bridget's Church
description: One of the world's largest amber altarpieces is housed within this reconstructed medieval church.

itemLabel: Archaeological Remains at Hala Targowa (Market Hall)
name: Archaeological Remains at Hala Targowa (Market Hall)
description: Several 12th-century ruins can be found inside this historical market.

name: Lunar Rover at Mariacka Street
description: During the renovation of this bas-relief, the constructors added one unusual element.

itemLabel: Beached Wreck of the Warship Grom II
name: Beached Wreck of the Warship Grom II
description: The rusting hulk of a Soviet warship sits on a Polish beach.

name: Gdański Lew Hewelion
description: Gdańsk's lion mascot features in a trail of bronze sculptures scattered all across the city.

The old city hall (built 1378-1492) has a museum inside showing off a nicely decorated room where the town council once met and some historic exhibits about the history of Gdańsk. There are also impressive photos of the destruction after World War II. It is possible to purchase tickets to the tower, which offers a great view of the surroundings and St. Mary's Church. }}

Impressive mansion, a symbol of the city's power in the 16th and 17th centuries, served as an exchange and as the seat of St. George and the brotherhoods of rich patricians. Now part of the Gdańsk History Museum. }}
Statue of Neptune, patron of the city, installed in 1549. During World War II, the statue was hidden. In 1954 it was put back to its original location on the Long Market.}}

Named after the merchant, Johann Uphagen, who bought this house in 1775. It was destroyed during the war in 1945, but completely rebuilt within ten years. In the 1990s, it was opened to the public. There are temporary exhibitions on the second floor. It is part of the Gdańsk History Museum. }}
Also called Upplands Gate. It was built in 1576 as part of the city's fortifications. Once the main entrance to the city where the Polish Kings were officially welcomed. }}
The viewing platform of the tower is open in summer months. This building also houses the Amber Museum. }}
Impressive houses stand along the river bank. They can be nicely observed from the other bank of Motława.}}

The former port crane is one of the most well-known buildings in Gdańsk. It is first mentioned in 1367, but was rebuilt several times since then. During World War II it was partially destroyed again. In 1962 after final reconstructions it was turned over to the National Maritime Museum. It now houses an exhibition about the former port of the city. The mechanism for lifting the crane can be observed as well.}}

One of the largest [[Gothic]] churches in Europe and one of the three (almost equal sizes) second largest brick churches in the world. There is space for more than 20,000 people in the church. It is possible to take the stairs to the tower (78 m), but the view is not as inspiring as the one from Main Town Hall. The church also contains a large astronomical clock from 1464. There are tickets to visit the church and tickets to the tower, sold in different places.}}
Differs from typical Gdańsk architecture.}}

Contains an organ built in the mid-18th century as the largest organ in Europe at that time with slightly fewer than 8,000 pipes. There are daily organ recitals which are generally free (with some exceptions).}}

Built in the 16th century. Its most famous resident was the councillor and mayor of Danzig, Johannes Hevelius, who was also an astronomer in his later life and a brewer in his earlier life. The building is now home to the Baltic Sea Culture Centre.}}
The current seat of the Gdańsk City Council.}}
Monument to the Fallen Shipyard Workers shot during communist regime in 1970.}}
Old mill (built 1350), with 18 water wheels up to 1939 produced 200 tonnes of flour daily, but is now a shopping centre.}}

A statue of the author Günter Grass, who was born in Gdańsk, facing his famous character Oskar Matzerath from ''The Tin Drum''. Installed in October 2015, six months after his death, and on his 88th anniversary.}}

Old city arsenal from 1605. Great example of Dutch design with astonishing stonework. These days the Great Armoury belongs to the Gdansk Academy of Fine Arts and visiting inside is only possible during art exhibitions which are organised from time to time by the Academy.}}
Part of the Gdańsk History Museum. Inside the museum you can also see a carillon and views from the top of the tower.}}

A centre dedicated to the history of Solidarity, a trade union that became the opposition to the communist government). Among other things, the building contains a museum and viewpoint at the roof terrace (freely accessible via elevator). There is free Wi-Fi in the building.}}

There is a small museum which documents the events that happened on 1 September 1939 at the beginning of World War II. It also contains a small active post office. Even if the museum is closed, the square in front has a great (and free) series of billboards summarizing the start of the war.}}

The ship was launched in 1948 as the first Polish ocean-going vessel and used as a coal and ore carrier. It was named after the "shock worker" Stanisław Sołdek. It is part of the National Maritime Museum.}}

itemLabel: Museum of the Second World War
description: A museum with recreations of World War II realities (Polish street of 1930, a shell-damaged scene with a T-34 tank), in an unusual skewed building.}}

Park with many information panels about the first battle of World War II that took place here in September 1939. You can also see disused bunkers and a crumbled command-post, as well as a large monument to those who fought in the battle. From the monument you have a view of the Nowy Port area and the lighthouse. The bus ride also takes you past the enormous (now defunct) shipyards.}}
A 28m high lighthouse built in 1893. It features a time ball which was used to synchronize clocks on ships.}}
A nice white-painted wooden pier. There is a small restaurant and an ice cream parlour.}}
Major orchestra for symphonic concerts and chamber music.}}
Guided tours (in English and Polish) are available.}}
Art Institute on the shipyard grounds. Exhibitions, concerts, performances. A bookshop, Zła Buka, has a selection of books on art and design.}}

The water is usually cold. Almost all of Gdańsk's coast consists of sandy beaches accessible for recreation. There are multiple areas with lifeguards, food stands and bars; the most popular ones are in Brzeźno and Jelitkowo. A less crowded one is in Stogi. The beach that's the furthest from the city centre (and thus not well accessible using public transport) is on Sobieszewo Island.}}
Take an evening walk down one of Europe's most picturesque streets.}}
Large fair held since 1260 during mid-July and mid-August every year.}}
ZTM offers a seasonal water tram service: route F5 ''Żabi Kruk - Westerplatte'' and F6 ''Targ Rybny - National Sailing Centre''. A single ticket costs 10 zł.}}
Festival of esteemed films taking place in June. There are many indoor and outdoor movie shows and concerts. Until 2017 the festival was organised in [[Katowice]].}}
Hand-embroidered items in traditional and contemporary designs and colours including clothing, tablecloths, napkins, curtains, and other regional folk art souvenirs.}}
Fresh produce in the basement level.}}
